## Key Findings

### Credit Score Is the Strongest Predictor

Credit score accounted for approximately 80.3% of approval outcomes.

Approval rates increased significantly as credit scores improved:

* 300–500: 10.7% approval rate
* 751–900: 99.4% approval rate

### Loan Term Influences Approval

Shorter loan terms demonstrated higher approval rates, suggesting lower perceived lending risk.

### Minimal Demographic Impact

Variables such as education level and employment type had little impact on approval decisions and should not heavily influence lending outcomes.

## Proposed Credit Risk Framework

| Tier       | Credit Score | Decision             |
| ---------- | ------------ | -------------------- |
| High       | 750+         | Automatic Approval   |
| Medium     | 650–749      | Conditional Approval |
| Borderline | 600–649      | Manual Review        |
| Low        | Below 600    | Reject               |

## Business Impact

The proposed framework can help organizations:

* Improve approval consistency
* Reduce subjective decision making
